wd\":\"/Users/alisha/Projects/wt/kiro-oneshot\",\"sessionId\":\"96a285b5-3eb1-4f66-8733-15f335183d35\",\"version\":\"2.1.63\",\"gitBranch\":\"alisha/kiro-oneshot\",\"slug\":\"snazzy-dreaming-badger\",\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"message\":{\"type\":\"user\",\"message\":{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":[{\"tool_use_id\":\"toolu_01Rfz49Wr92BugcrT5qtbY8s\",\"type\":\"tool_result\",\"content\":\"     1→# Kiro Agent Integration\\n     2→\\n     3→Implementation one-pager for the Kiro (Amazon AI coding CLI) agent integration.\\n     4→\\n     5→## Identity\\n     6→\\n     7→| Field | Value |\\n     8→|-------|-------|\\n     9→| Package | `kiro` |\\n    10→| Registry Key | `kiro` |\\n    11→| Agent Type | `Kiro` |\\n    12→| Binary | `kiro-cli` |\\n    13→| Preview | Yes |\\n    14→| Protected Dir | `.kiro` |\\n    15→\\n    16→## Hook Events (5 CLI + 4 IDE)\\n    17→\\n    18→| Kiro Hook (camelCase) | CLI Subcommand (kebab-case) | EventType | Notes |\\n    19→|----------------------|----------------------------|-----------|-------|\\n    20→| `agentSpawn` | `agent-spawn` | `SessionStart` | Agent initializes |\\n    21→| `userPromptSubmit` | `user-prompt-submit` | `TurnStart` | stdin includes `prompt` field |\\n    22→| `preToolUse` | `pre-tool-use` | `nil, nil` | Pass-through |\\n    23→| `postToolUse` | `post-tool-use` | `nil, nil` | Pass-through |\\n    24→| `stop` | `stop` | `TurnEnd` | Checkpoint trigger |\\n    25→\\n    26→No `SessionEnd` hook exists — sessions end implicitly (similar to Cursor).\\n    27→\\n    28→## Hook Configuration\\n    29→\\n    30→### CLI Agent Hooks\\n    31→\\n    32→**File:** `.kiro/agents/entire.json`\\n    33→\\n    34→We own the entire file — no round-trip preservation needed (unlike Cursor's shared `hooks.json`).\\n    35→\\n    36→**Format:**\\n    37→```json\\n    38→{\\n    39→  \\\"name\\\": \\\"entire\\\",\\n    40→  \\\"tools\\\": [\\\"read\\\", \\\"write\\\", \\\"shell\\\", \\\"grep\\\", \\\"glob\\\", \\\"aws\\\", \\\"report\\\",\\n    41→            \\\"introspect\\\", \\\"knowledge\\\", \\\"thinking\\\", \\\"todo\\\", \\\"delegate\\\"],\\n    42→  \\\"hooks\\\": {\\n    43→    \\\"agentSpawn\\\": [{\\\"command\\\": \\\"entire hooks kiro agent-spawn\\\"}],\\n    44→    \\\"userPromptSubmit\\\": [{\\\"command\\\": \\\"entire hooks kiro user-prompt-submit\\\"}],\\n    45→    \\\"preToolUse\\\": [{\\\"command\\\": \\\"entire hooks kiro pre-tool-use\\\"}],\\n    46→    \\\"postToolUse\\\": [{\\\"command\\\": \\\"entire hooks kiro post-tool-use\\\"}],\\n    47→    \\\"stop\\\": [{\\\"command\\\": \\\"entire hooks kiro stop\\\"}]\\n    48→  }\\n    49→}\\n    50→```\\n    51→\\n    52→Note: The file is a Kiro agent definition. Hooks must be nested under the `hooks` field.\\n    53→Required top-level fields: `name`. Optional: `$schema`, `description`, `prompt`, `mcpServers`,\\n    54→`tools`, `toolAliases`, `allowedTools`, `resources`, `hooks`, `toolsSettings`, `model`, etc.\\n    55→\\n    56→**Important:** The `tools` array must include all default Kiro tools. Without it, `--agent entire`\\n    57→restricts the model to zero tools. The tool names come from `~/.kiro/agents/agent_config.json.example`.\\n    58→\\n    59→### IDE Hook Configuration\\n    60→\\n    61→**Directory:** `.kiro/hooks/`\\n    62→\\n    63→The Kiro IDE (VS Code extension) reads hooks from individual `.kiro/hooks/*.kiro.hook` files.\\n    64→Unlike CLI hooks (nested in `entire.json`), each IDE hook is a standalone JSON file.\\n    65→\\n    66→**IDE hook files installed (4 total):**\\n    67→\\n    68→| File | `when.type` | Command |\\n    69→|------|-------------|---------|\\n    70→| `entire-prompt-submit.kiro.hook` | `promptSubmit` | `entire hooks kiro user-prompt-submit` |\\n    71→| `entire-stop.kiro.hook` | `agentStop` | `entire hooks kiro stop` |\\n    72→| `entire-pre-tool-use.kiro.hook` | `preToolUse` | `entire hooks kiro pre-tool-use` |\\n    73→| `entire-post-tool-use.kiro.hook` | `postToolUse` | `entire hooks kiro post-tool-use` |\\n    74→\\n    75→No `agentSpawn` IDE hook — the IDE has no such trigger. The first `promptSubmit` serves as session start.\\n    76→\\n    77→**Format:**\\n    78→```json\\n    79→{\\n    80→  \\\"enabled\\\": true,\\n    81→  \\\"name\\\": \\\"entire-prompt-submit\\\",\\n    82→  \\\"description\\\": \\\"Entire CLI promptSubmit hook\\\",\\n    83→  \\\"version\\\": \\\"1\\\",\\n    84→  \\\"when\\\": {\\n    85→    \\\"type\\\": \\\"promptSubmit\\\"\\n    86→  },\\n    87→  \\\"then\\\": {\\n    88→    \\\"type\\\": \\\"runCommand\\\",\\n    89→    \\\"command\\\": \\\"entire hooks kiro user-prompt-submit\\\"\\n    90→  }\\n    91→}\\n    92→```\\n    93→\\n    94→**Key difference from CLI hooks:** IDE hooks deliver data via environment variables (e.g.,\\n    95→`USER_PROMPT` for the user's prompt) rather than JSON on stdin. The lifecycle parsers handle\\n    96→empty stdin gracefully by reading from environment variables as a fallback.\\n    97→\\n    98→## Agent Activation\\n    99→\\n   100→Hooks only fire when `--agent entire` is passed to `kiro-cli chat`. Without this flag,\\n   101→`.kiro/agents/entire.json` is not loaded and hooks do not execute.\\n   102→\\n   103→IDE hooks in `.kiro/hooks/` are loaded automatically by the Kiro IDE without requiring\\n   104→an explicit agent flag.\\n   105→\\n   106→**`--no-interactive` mode:** Does not fire agent hooks. All E2E tests use interactive (tmux) mode.\\n   107→\\n   108→**TUI prompt indicator:** `!>` in trust-all mode (with `-a` flag). The `Credits:` line\\n   109→appears after each agent response and serves as a reliable completion marker.\\n   110→\\n   111→## Hook Data Delivery\\n   112→\\n   113→### CLI Mode (stdin JSON)\\n   114→\\n   115→CLI hooks (`kiro-cli chat --agent entire`) receive a JSON structure on stdin:\\n   116→```json\\n   117→{\\n   118→  \\\"hook_event_name\\\": \\\"userPromptSubmit\\\",\\n   119→  \\\"cwd\\\": \\\"/path/to/repo\\\",\\n   120→  \\\"prompt\\\": \\\"user message\\\",\\n   121→  \\\"tool_name\\\": \\\"fs_write\\\",\\n   122→  \\\"tool_input\\\": \\\"...\\\",\\n   123→  \\\"tool_response\\\": \\\"...\\\"\\n   124→}\\n   125→```\\n   126→\\n   127→Fields are populated based on the hook event — `prompt` only for `userPromptSubmit`, tool fields only for tool hooks.\\n   128→\\n   129→### IDE Mode (environment variables)\\n   130→\\n   131→IDE hooks (`.kiro/hooks/*.kiro.hook`) receive **no stdin**. Data is delivered via environment variables:\\n   132→- `USER_PROMPT` — the user's prompt text (for `promptSubmit` hooks)\\n   133→\\n   134→The lifecycle parsers handle empty stdin gracefully: if stdin is empty, they fall back to reading\\n   135→environment variables for prompt data and use `paths.WorktreeRoot()` for CWD.\\n   136→\\n   137→## Transcript Storage\\n   138→\\n   139→**Source:** SQLite database at `~/Library/Application Support/kiro-cli/data.sqlite3` (macOS)\\n   140→or `~/.local/share/kiro-cli/data.sqlite3` (Linux).\\n   141→\\n   142→**Table:** `conversations_v2`\\n   143→- `key` column: CWD path (used for lookup)\\n   144→- `value` column: JSON blob with conversation data\\n   145→- `updated_at` column: timestamp for ordering\\n   146→\\n   147→**Conversation JSON structure:**\\n   148→```json\\n   149→{\\n   150→  \\\"conversation_id\\\": \\\"uuid-v4\\\",\\n   151→  \\\"history\\\": [\\n   152→    {\\\"role\\\": \\\"user\\\", \\\"content\\\": [{\\\"type\\\": \\\"text\\\", \\\"text\\\": \\\"...\\\"}]},\\n   153→    {\\\"role\\\": \\\"assistant\\\", \\\"content\\\": [{\\\"type\\\": \\\"text\\\", \\\"text\\\": \\\"...\\\"}, {\\\"type\\\": \\\"tool_use\\\", \\\"name\\\": \\\"fs_write\\\", \\\"input\\\": {...}}]},\\n   154→    {\\\"role\\\": \\\"request_metadata\\\", \\\"input_tokens\\\": 150, \\\"output_tokens\\\": 80}\\n   155→  ]\\n   156→}\\n   157→```\\n   158→\\n   159→## Session ID Discovery\\n   160→\\n   161→Hook stdin does not include session ID. We query SQLite by CWD:\\n   162→```sql\\n   163→SELECT json_extract(value, '$.conversation_id')\\n   164→FROM conversations_v2\\n   165→WHERE key = '<cwd>'\\n   166→ORDER BY updated_at DESC LIMIT 1\\n   167→```\\n   168→\\n   169→## SQLite Access Strategy\\n   170→\\n   171→Uses `sqlite3` CLI (pre-installed on macOS/Linux) rather than a Go library to avoid CGO dependencies. Same approach as OpenCode's `opencode export` CLI.\\n   172→\\n   173→**Test mock:** `ENTIRE_TEST_KIRO_MOCK_DB=1` env var causes the agent to skip SQLite queries and use pre-written mock files.\\n   174→\\n   175→## File Modification Tools\\n   176→\\n   177→Tools that modify files on disk:\\n   178→- `fs_write` — write file content\\n   179→- `str_replace` — string replacement in files\\n   180→- `create_file` — create new files\\n   181→- `write_file` — write/overwrite files\\n   182→- `edit_file` — edit existing files\\n   183→\\n   184→## Caching\\n   185→\\n   186→Transcript data is cached to `.entire/tmp/<sessionID>.json` (same pattern as OpenCode).\\n   187→\"}]},\"uuid\":\"921546f2-a204-4118-becf-4cb700cdef63\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-04T19:12:09.114Z\"},\"normalizedMessages\":[],\"type\":\"agent_progress\",\"prompt\":\"\",\"agentId\":\"a91c478933bd16454\"},\"toolUseID\":\"agent_msg_01U3edxyPXArhRyJJmVWskAo\",\"parentToolUseID\":\"toolu_0146MFDKWDJEt2zv3f1RZZM9\",\"uuid\":\"1557f86e-7f46-4279-931a-9adf7e4c118b\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-04T19:12:09.279Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"1557f86e-7f46-4279-931a-9adf7e4c118b\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/alisha/Projects/wt/kiro-oneshot\",\"sessionId\":\"96a285b5-3eb1-4f66-8733-15f335183d35\",\"version\":\"2.1.63\",\"gitBranch\":\"alisha/kiro-oneshot\",\"slug\":\"snazzy-dreaming-badger\",\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"message\":{\"type\":\"assistant\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-04T19:12:09.347Z\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001\",\"id\":\"msg_01U1MCF17HugpGZwHSMWzSqm\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"tool_use\",\"id\":\"toolu_01StfcBpqsHx3WKm52jTbS4Z\",\"name\":\"Read\",\"input\":{\"file_path\":\"/Users/alisha/Projects/wt/kiro-oneshot/docs/architecture/agent-guide.md\",\"limit\":200},\"caller\":{\"type\":\"direct\"}}],\"stop_reason\":null,\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":7,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":1842,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":80980,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":1842},\"output_tokens\":1,\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"inference_geo\":\"not_available\"},\"context_management\":null},\"requestId\":\"req_011CYia4cvQDaJgRqne3Yxoa\",\"uuid\":\"6d6f2fd6-2bed-4d61-bf70-c73fae343e6e\"},\"normalizedMessages\":[],\"type\":\"agent_progress\",\"prompt\":\"\",\"agentId\":\"a91c478933bd16454\"},\"toolUseID\":\"agent_msg_01U3edxyPXArhRyJJmVWskAo\",\"parentToolUseID\":\"toolu_0146MFDKWDJEt2zv3f1RZZM9\",\"uuid\":\"68cbad07-cfb4-4742-8219-b719303b249a\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-04T19:12:09.347Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"68cbad07-cfb4-4742-8219-b719303b249a\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/alisha/Projects/wt/kiro-oneshot\",\"sessionId\":\"96a285b5-3eb1-4f66-8733-15f335183d35\",\"version\":\"2.1.63\",\"gitBranch\":\"alisha/kiro-oneshot\",\"slug\":\"snazzy-dreaming-badger\",\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"message\":{\"type\":\"user\",\"message\":{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":[{\"tool_use_id\":\"toolu_01StfcBpqsHx3WKm52jTbS4Z\",\"type\":\"tool_result\",\"content\":\"     1→# Agent Implementation Guide\\n     2→\\n     3→Before implementing, read the [Agent Integration Checklist](agent-integration-checklist.md) for design principles (full transcript storage, native format preservation) and validation criteria.\\n     4→\\n     5→## Architecture Overview\\n     6→\\n     7→The Entire CLI uses **inversion of control** for agent integration: agents are passive data providers that translate their native hook payloads into normalized lifecycle events, and the framework handles all orchestration (state transitions, file detection, checkpoint saving, metadata generation). The flow is:\\n     8→\\n     9→```\\n    10→Agent hook invocation → ParseHookEvent() → Event → DispatchLifecycleEvent() → framework actions\\n    11→```\\n    12→\\n    13→An agent never calls strategy methods or manages session state directly. It only answers questions: \\\"What event just happened?\\\" and \\\"What does the transcript say?\\\"\\n    14→\\n    15→## Quick Reference\\n    16→\\n    17→### Core Interface (`Agent`)\\n    18→\\n    19→Every agent must implement all 19 methods on the `Agent` interface:\\n    20→\\n    21→| Group | Method | Purpose |\\n    22→|-------|--------|---------|\\n    23→| **Identity** | `Name()` | Registry key (e.g., `\\\"claude-code\\\"`) |\\n    24→| | `Type()` | Display name for metadata (e.g., `\\\"Claude Code\\\"`) |\\n    25→| | `Description()` | Human-readable description for UI |\\n    26→| | `DetectPresence()` | Check if agent is configured in the repo |\\n    27→| | `ProtectedDirs()` | Directories to preserve during rewind |\\n    28→| **Event Mapping** | `HookNames()` | Hook verbs that become CLI subcommands |\\n    29→| | `ParseHookEvent()` | **Core contribution surface** - translate native hooks to Events |\\n    30→| **Transcript** | `ReadTranscript()` | Read raw transcript bytes |\\n    31→| | `ChunkTranscript()` | Split large transcripts at format-aware boundaries |\\n    32→| | `ReassembleTranscript()` | Recombine chunks into a single transcript |\\n    33→| **Session Management** | `GetHookConfigPath()` | Path to hook config file |\\n    34→| | `SupportsHooks()` | Whether agent supports lifecycle hooks |\\n    35→| | `ParseHookInput()` | Parse hook callback input from stdin |\\n    36→| | `GetSessionID()` | Extract session ID from hook input |\\n    37→| | `GetSessionDir()` | Where agent stores session data |\\n    38→| | `ResolveSessionFile()` | Path to session transcript file |\\n    39→| | `ReadSession()` | Read session data from agent's storage |\\n    40→| | `WriteSession()` | Write session data for resumption |\\n    41→| | `FormatResumeCommand()` | Command to resume a session |\\n    42→\\n    43→### Optional Interfaces\\n    44→\\n    45→| Interface | Methods | When to implement |\\n    46→|-----------|---------|-------------------|\\n    47→| `HookSupport` | `InstallHooks`, `UninstallHooks`, `AreHooksInstalled`, `GetSupportedHooks` | Agent uses a config file for hook registration (e.g., `settings.json`) |\\n    48→| `HookHandler` | `GetHookNames` | **Required for CLI hook registration** — `entire hooks <agent> <verb>` subcommands are only created for agents implementing this interface. Typically delegates to `HookNames()`. |\\n    49→| `TranscriptAnalyzer` | `GetTranscriptPosition`, `ExtractModifiedFilesFromOffset`, `ExtractPrompts`, `ExtractSummary` | You want richer checkpoints with transcript-derived file lists and prompts |\\n    50→| `TranscriptPreparer` | `PrepareTranscript` | Agent writes transcripts asynchronously and needs a flush/sync step |\\n    51→| `TokenCalculator` | `CalculateTokenUsage` | Agent's transcript contains token usage data |\\n    52→| `SubagentAwareExtractor` | `ExtractAllModifiedFiles`, `CalculateTotalTokenUsage` | Agent spawns subagents (like Claude Code's Task tool) |\\n    53→| `HookResponseWriter` | `WriteHookResponse` | Agent can display messages from hook responses (e.g., session start banner). Claude Code uses JSON `systemMessage` on stdout; Factory AI Droid uses plain text on stdout. |\\n    54→| `FileWatcher` | `GetWatchPaths`, `OnFileChange` | Agent doesn't support hooks; uses file-based detection instead |\\n    55→\\n    56→## Step-by-Step Implementation Guide\\n    57→\\n    58→### Step 1: Create Package\\n    59→\\n    60→Create a new directory under `cmd/entire/cli/agent/`:\\n    61→\\n    62→```\\n    63→cmd/entire/cli/agent/youragent/\\n    64→├── youragent.go          # Core Agent implementation + init()\\n    65→├── lifecycle.go          # ParseHookEvent + compile-time assertions\\n    66→├── types.go              # Hook input structs, transcript types, tool constants\\n    67→├── hooks.go              # HookSupport implementation (if applicable)\\n    68→├── transcript.go         # TranscriptAnalyzer implementation (if applicable)\\n    69→├── lifecycle_test.go     # Tests for ParseHookEvent\\n    70→├── hooks_test.go         # Tests for hook installation\\n    71→└── transcript_test.go    # Tests for transcript analysis\\n    72→```\\n    73→\\n    74→### Step 2: Define Types (`types.go`)\\n    75→\\n    76→Define structs matching your agent's native hook JSON payloads:\\n    77→\\n    78→```go\\n    79→package youragent\\n    80→\\n    81→// Settings file structure (for HookSupport)\\n    82→type YourAgentSettings struct {\\n    83→    Hooks YourAgentHooks `json:\\\"hooks\\\"`\\n    84→}\\n    85→\\n    86→type YourAgentHooks struct {\\n    87→    SessionStart []HookMatcher `json:\\\"SessionStart,omitempty\\\"`\\n    88→    SessionEnd   []HookMatcher `json:\\\"SessionEnd,omitempty\\\"`\\n    89→    // ... other hook types your agent supports\\n    90→}\\n    91→\\n    92→type HookMatcher struct {\\n    93→    Matcher string      `json:\\\"matcher,omitempty\\\"`\\n    94→    Hooks   []HookEntry `json:\\\"hooks\\\"`\\n    95→}\\n    96→\\n    97→type HookEntry struct {\\n    98→    Type    string `json:\\\"type\\\"`\\n    99→    Command string `json:\\\"command\\\"`\\n   100→}\\n   101→\\n   102→// Hook input structs - match your agent's JSON payloads\\n   103→\\n   104→type sessionInfoRaw struct {\\n   105→    SessionID      string `json:\\\"session_id\\\"`\\n   106→    TranscriptPath string `json:\\\"transcript_path\\\"`\\n   107→}\\n   108→\\n   109→type promptInputRaw struct {\\n   110→    SessionID      string `json:\\\"session_id\\\"`\\n   111→    TranscriptPath string `json:\\\"transcript_path\\\"`\\n   112→    Prompt         string `json:\\\"prompt\\\"`\\n   113→}\\n   114→\\n   115→// Tool constants - tools in your agent that modify files\\n   116→const (\\n   117→    ToolWrite = \\\"write_file\\\"\\n   118→    ToolEdit  = \\\"edit_file\\\"\\n   119→)\\n   120→\\n   121→var FileModificationTools = []string{ToolWrite, ToolEdit}\\n   122→```\\n   123→\\n   124→### Step 3: Implement Core Agent Interface (`youragent.go`)\\n   125→\\n   126→```go\\n   127→package youragent\\n   128→\\n   129→import (\\n   130→    \\\"errors\\\"\\n   131→    \\\"fmt\\\"\\n   132→    \\\"io\\\"\\n   133→    \\\"os\\\"\\n   134→    \\\"path/filepath\\\"\\n   135→\\n   136→    \\\"github.com/entireio/cli/cmd/entire/cli/agent\\\"\\n   137→    \\\"github.com/entireio/cli/cmd/entire/cli/paths\\\"\\n   138→)\\n   139→\\n   140→//nolint:gochecknoinits // Agent self-registration is the intended pattern\\n   141→func init() {\\n   142→    agent.Register(\\\"your-agent\\\", NewYourAgent)\\n   143→}\\n   144→\\n   145→type YourAgent struct{}\\n   146→\\n   147→func NewYourAgent() agent.Agent {\\n   148→    return &YourAgent{}\\n   149→}\\n   150→\\n   151→// --- Identity ---\\n   152→\\n   153→func (a *YourAgent) Name() agent.AgentName    { return \\\"your-agent\\\" }\\n   154→func (a *YourAgent) Type() agent.AgentType     { return \\\"Your Agent\\\" }\\n   155→func (a *YourAgent) Description() string       { return \\\"Your Agent - description here\\\" }\\n   156→func (a *YourAgent) ProtectedDirs() []string   { return []string{\\\".youragent\\\"} }\\n   157→\\n   158→func (a *YourAgent) DetectPresence() (bool, error) {\\n   159→    repoRoot, err := paths.RepoRoot()\\n   160→    if err != nil {\\n   161→        repoRoot = \\\".\\\"\\n   162→    }\\n   163→    _, err = os.Stat(filepath.Join(repoRoot, \\\".youragent\\\"))\\n   164→    if err == nil {\\n   165→        return true, nil\\n   166→    }\\n   167→    return false, nil\\n   168→}\\n   169→\\n   170→// --- Transcript Storage ---\\n   171→\\n   172→func (a *YourAgent) ReadTranscript(sessionRef string) ([]byte, error) {\\n   173→    data, err := os.ReadFile(sessionRef)\\n   174→    if err != nil {\\n   175→        return nil, fmt.Errorf(\\\"failed to read transcript: %w\\\", err)\\n   176→    }\\n   177→    return data, nil\\n   178→}\\n   179→\\n   180→func (a *YourAgent) ChunkTranscript(content []byte, maxSize int) ([][]byte, error) {\\n   181→    // Use JSONL chunking for line-based formats\\n   182→    return agent.ChunkJSONL(content, maxSize)\\n   183→    // Or implement format-specific chunking (see geminicli for JSON example)\\n   184→}\\n   185→\\n   186→func (a *YourAgent) ReassembleTranscript(chunks [][]byte) ([]byte, error) {\\n   187→    return agent.ReassembleJSONL(chunks), nil\\n   188→}\\n   189→\\n   190→// --- Session Management ---\\n   191→\\n   192→func (a *YourAgent) GetHookConfigPath() string                     { return \\\".youragent/settings.json\\\" }\\n   193→func (a *YourAgent) SupportsHooks() bool                           { return true }\\n   194→func (a *YourAgent) GetSessionID(input *agent.HookInput) string    { return input.SessionID }\\n   195→func (a *YourAgent) FormatResumeCommand(sessionID string) string   { return \\\"youragent --resume \\\" + sessionID }\\n   196→\\n   197→// ParseHookInput is part of the Agent interface and is called by integration tests.\\n   198→// Provide a real implementation that populates at least SessionID and SessionRef.\\n   199→func (a *YourAgent) ParseHookInput(hookType agent.HookType, r io.Reader) (*agent.HookInput, error) {\\n   200→    raw, err := agent.ReadAndParseHookInput[sessionInfoRaw](r)\"}]},\"uuid\":\"6548ec6d-4954-436f-9f1f-58b7e5847c9f\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-04T19:12:09.365Z\"},\"normalizedMessages\":[],\"type\":\"agent_progress\",\"prompt\":\"\",\"agentId\":\"a91c478933bd16454\"},\"toolUseID\":\"agent_msg_01U3edxyPXArhRyJJmVWskAo\",\"parentToolUseID\":\"toolu_0146MFDKWDJEt2zv3f1RZZM9\",\"uuid\":\"96af0673-dd68-4502-bb8d-97ad21713131\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-04T19:12:09.365Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"96a